@jbrockmendel I guess the issue is that the current behavior is that anything that *could* be a time zone name but isn't is just ignored. Likely if we start throwing an error instead of just silently ignoring those "potential tzname" components, we'll get a *lot* of flack when people parsing dates that look like `2014-03-12 12:30 CST` without passing `tzinfos` pick up the change, since, unless they happen to be on a machine where `CST` is one of the time zone names, that will look like an arbitrary string and throw an error.

One option we have is to go through something like [this](https://www.timeanddate.com/time/zones/) and see if we can write an expression that matches everything in there, but doesn't match anything else. It could start with "any individual letter" + "anything ending with T", restricted to 3-5 characters.

At some point we might want to start throwing deprecation warnings that arbitrary time zone abbreviations with unspecified `tzinfos` will no longer be supported.

